hire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1350–15 March 1417":"about 1350–15 March 1417","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","Abt 1395":"about 1395","1425":"1425","1325":"1325","15 March 1417":"15 March 1417","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1350":"about 1350","1428":"1428","1417":"1417","about 1395":"about 1395","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Rissheton, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rishton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rushton  . Early bearers: Aleander Rishton, 1560 in   IGI   (Great Harwood, Lancs); Anna Rishton, 1598, Elizabeth Rushton, 1635 in   IGI   (Altham, Lancs); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["English: unexplained, but perhaps a variant of   Apps  ; compare Robert  <i>Apps</i>, 1587 in   IGI   (East Coker, Somerset)."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph Rishton was born about 1350, in Rishton, Lancashire, England as the son of Robert de Rishton. He married Cecilia about 1395, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 15 March 1417, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1350–15 March 1417":"umbes 1350–15. märts 1417","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","1425":"1425","1325":"1325","15 March 1417":"15. märts 1417","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1350":"umbes 1350","142